 "modules": [
  {
   "title": "Module 1 · Expansion",
   "html": "<p>Use the distributive law $a(b+c)=ab+ac$ and identities:</p>$$(a+b)^2 = a^2 + 2ab + b^2$$$$(a-b)^2 = a^2 - 2ab + b^2$$$$(a+b)(a-b) = a^2 - b^2$$",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Expand $(2x+3)^2$.",
     "a": "$(2x)^2 + 2\\cdot 2x\\cdot 3 + 3^2 = 4x^2 + 12x + 9$."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 2 · Factorisation of Quadratics",
   "html": "<p>For $x^2 + bx + c$, find two numbers whose sum is $b$ and product is $c$. For $ax^2+bx+c$ with $a\\ne 1$, use the AC method: find factors of $ac$ that add to $b$, split the middle term and factor by grouping.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Factorise $x^2 + 7x + 12$.",
     "a": "$3+4=7$, $3\\cdot 4=12$: $(x+3)(x+4)$."
    },
    {
     "q": "Factorise $2x^2 + 7x + 3$.",
     "a": "$ac=6$; factors of 6 summing to 7 are 6 and 1. Split: $2x^2 + 6x + x + 3 = 2x(x+3)+1(x+3) = (2x+1)(x+3)$."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 3 · Linear Equations & Word Problems",
   "html": "<p>Isolate the variable using inverse operations. In word problems, define a variable, translate the words into an equation, solve, and check.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Solve $3(x-2) = 15$.",
     "a": "$x-2 = 5 \\Rightarrow x = 7$."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 4 · Change of Subject & Substitution",
   "html": "<p>Treat the target letter as the unknown; use the same rules as solving equations to isolate it.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Make $r$ the subject of $A = \\pi r^2$.",
     "a": "$r^2 = A/\\pi \\Rightarrow r = \\sqrt{A/\\pi}$."
    },
    {
     "q": "If $v = u + at$, find $t$.",
     "a": "$t = (v-u)/a$."
    }
   ]
  }
 ],
